snippet.textDisplay: A tumbleweed is a structural part of the above-ground anatomy of a number of species of plants, a diaspore that, once it is mature and dry, detaches from its root or stem, and rolls due to the force of the wind. In most such species, the tumbleweed is in effect the entire plant apart from the rootsystem, but in other plants, a hollow fruit or an inflorescence might serve the function.[1]Tumbleweed species occur most commonly in steppe and arid ecosystems, where frequent wind and the open environment permit rolling without prohibitive obstruction.

In most such species, the tumbleweed is in effect the entire plant apart from the rootsystem, but in other plants, a hollow fruit or an inflorescence might serve the function.[1]Tumbleweed species occur most commonly in steppe and arid ecosystems, where frequent wind and the open environment permit rolling without prohibitive obstruction.

Also, the words "brown snowdrift."

snippet.textDisplay: Is there more than one variety of tumbleweed? I'm from a farming community in Western Kansas and we used to (as a joke) decorate a tumbleweed as if it were a Christmas tree. snippet.textDisplay:
Ah, America. Famous for all the things that aren't native to it in the slightest...
Humans... Horses... Tumbleweed... Cows... Armadillo's that can curl into balls...


I've been lied to for all my life... To think, I used to believe all of this was really American... And also that America was just New York and Texas, and everyone was a cowboy (which I have had confirmed on multiple occassions that this part is still the case, so that one isn't a lie).



(Nine-bands are native to North America, but only Three-bands can curl into balls, and they're native to South America)

snippet.textDisplay:
Huh. I've never seen a tumbleweed before, and mentally I associate it with the past, when really it's an association with America, because in fact they're still around.

And yet this video shows, that bizarrely, this isn't a native species, and actually comes from russia?!

Now I kinda wanna see where in Russia you get these...
And also what it is in their native environment that has kept them from literally overrunning all of Europe and Asia...
